Yes, go!

00:47:54.673 --> 00:47:56.637
AUDIENCE: I didn't quite
catch what you said,

00:47:56.637 --> 00:48:01.759
2D animation is harder
than 3D animation.

00:48:01.759 --> 00:48:04.050
LUIGI GUATIERI: Have you ever
seen an old Disney movie?

00:48:07.490 --> 00:48:09.360
They usually had
armies of what they

00:48:09.360 --> 00:48:14.410
called in-betweeners, in that
there would be a key frame

00:48:14.410 --> 00:48:14.910
artist.

00:48:14.910 --> 00:48:17.282
He would draw Snow
White dancing like this.

00:48:17.282 --> 00:48:18.990
And then there would
be the poor bastards

00:48:18.990 --> 00:48:23.410
who had to draw every
single frame of her going

00:48:23.410 --> 00:48:26.430
like this, all 30 or 40 frames.

00:48:26.430 --> 00:48:30.780
So in a game, if you want
hand-drawn animations that

00:48:30.780 --> 00:48:33.094
look really
interesting and nice,

00:48:33.094 --> 00:48:34.760
you have to get someone
who will bother.

00:48:34.760 --> 00:48:37.020
Like, Street Fighter III
is a great exam-- or King

00:48:37.020 --> 00:48:40.070
of Fighters-- those games
take forever to animate,

00:48:40.070 --> 00:48:41.570
because they are
done in that Disney

00:48:41.570 --> 00:48:44.090
style, in terms of
just frame by frame

00:48:44.090 --> 00:48:45.530
by frame by frame by frame.

00:48:45.530 --> 00:48:47.740
But the other thing
they have to worry about

00:48:47.740 --> 00:48:50.430
is to make sure that the hit
points are in the right place,

00:48:50.430 --> 00:48:53.070
that the collision boxes
are in the right place.

00:48:53.070 --> 00:48:55.090
It takes a lot of
time to do that.

00:48:55.090 --> 00:48:57.160
That's why when I
mentioned tweening

00:48:57.160 --> 00:49:00.145
as a quick way of
trying to mimic that,

00:49:00.145 --> 00:49:01.700
it doesn't look as good usually.

00:49:01.700 --> 00:49:04.090
And in a lot of games that
use a lot of tweening,

00:49:04.090 --> 00:49:07.010
like Limbo, for example, they
hide it with silhouettes.

00:49:07.010 --> 00:49:11.576
Because you get these
weird seams and it

00:49:11.576 --> 00:49:12.450
doesn't look as good.

00:49:12.450 --> 00:49:14.783
There are obviously tools
that help with this like Flash

00:49:14.783 --> 00:49:16.320
animation.

00:49:16.320 --> 00:49:20.660
You can sort of do an in-between
of tweening and hand animation.

00:49:20.660 --> 00:49:22.950
But sort of frame by
frame, sprite animation,

00:49:22.950 --> 00:49:25.240
takes a long time.

00:49:25.240 --> 00:49:27.530
And 3D-- I mean, it's
easier, because it's all

00:49:27.530 --> 00:49:28.660
tweening usually.

00:49:28.660 --> 00:49:33.180
Unless you have some character
that transforms all the time.

00:49:33.180 --> 00:49:36.565
It's the same way in 2D,
in that a 3D arm that

00:49:36.565 --> 00:49:38.530
is rigged like this
is always going

00:49:38.530 --> 00:49:41.030
to look like this because you
can just sort of manipulate it

00:49:41.030 --> 00:49:42.490
in 3D space.

00:49:42.490 --> 00:49:45.090
Doing this in 3D is really easy.

00:49:45.090 --> 00:49:49.160
Doing this in 2D takes forever,
if you know what I mean.

00:49:49.160 --> 00:49:50.296
That answer your question?

00:49:50.296 --> 00:49:51.404
AUDIENCE: Kind of.

00:49:51.404 --> 00:49:52.820
LUIGI GUATIERI:
Is there something

00:49:52.820 --> 00:49:55.065
you need me to follow up on?

00:49:55.065 --> 00:49:56.648
AUDIENCE: I kind of
see what you mean,

00:49:56.648 --> 00:49:58.064
like you have to
draw every frame.

00:49:58.064 --> 00:49:59.757
LUIGI GUATIERI: Yeah.

00:49:59.757 --> 00:50:02.172
AUDIENCE: Unity has a very
cool way to go around this.

00:50:02.172 --> 00:50:06.036
Like, [INAUDIBLE] that's
actually 3D that is snap-shot

00:50:06.036 --> 00:50:07.904
into 2D, so they
don't have to worry--

00:50:07.904 --> 00:50:09.820
LUIGI GUATIERI: Yeah,
that's one way to do it.

00:50:09.820 --> 00:50:11.800
That's one way to
solve it, but then you

00:50:11.800 --> 00:50:13.780
have to make all your
models in 3D first,

00:50:13.780 --> 00:50:17.410
and then animate in 3D, which
the modeling process takes time

00:50:17.410 --> 00:50:19.120
as well.

00:50:19.120 --> 00:50:21.030
And then you have to
think about-- all right,

00:50:21.030 --> 00:50:23.220
I have 2D artists.

00:50:23.220 --> 00:50:24.160
Can I do this?

00:50:24.160 --> 00:50:26.362
No, I need a 3D
artist to do this.

00:50:26.362 --> 00:50:27.820
It's just something
to think about.

00:50:27.820 --> 00:50:31.140
But yeah, that's a way around
it that a lot of people use.

00:50:31.140 --> 00:50:32.188
Yes, go.

00:50:32.188 --> 00:50:34.354
AUDIENCE: Does it make sense
for a software engineer

00:50:34.354 --> 00:50:37.672
to learn the basics of
drawing, so that they better

00:50:37.672 --> 00:50:40.376
understand maybe the artists
and give more reasonable tasks?

00:50:40.376 --> 00:50:42.584
LUIGI GUATIERI: Sorry, could
you repeat the question?

00:50:42.584 --> 00:50:44.994
AUDIENCE: So does it make
sense for a software engineer

00:50:44.994 --> 00:50:48.850
to learn the basics of drawing,
so that you better understand

00:50:48.850 --> 00:50:53.200
artists and maybe give
more reasonable tasks?

00:50:53.200 --> 00:50:55.120
LUIGI GUATIERI: Yes.

00:50:55.120 --> 00:50:58.390
Programmers, designers, software
engineers should totally

00:50:58.390 --> 00:51:02.340
try to understand the basics
of art and color theory

00:51:02.340 --> 00:51:07.890
and the process of making
art, so when it comes time

00:51:07.890 --> 00:51:10.800
to either advising the artist
on what they need to change

00:51:10.800 --> 00:51:16.360
or what might not fit, you
have some understanding

00:51:16.360 --> 00:51:18.050
of all right, these
colors go together.

00:51:18.050 --> 00:51:20.220
These colors don't go together.

00:51:20.220 --> 00:51:22.530
Could you composition
this a little better,

00:51:22.530 --> 00:51:26.680
so you like put these down
here and that over there.

00:51:26.680 --> 00:51:29.385
But again, a lot of art
direction is about contrasting,

00:51:29.385 --> 00:51:31.590
and composition, and
color is a big one.

00:51:31.590 --> 00:51:36.990
I didn't really talk about
color, color theory, too much.

00:51:36.990 --> 00:51:39.570
Like for instance, Jenna in
Little Worlds Interactive,

00:51:39.570 --> 00:51:41.200
when I worked with
her, she already

00:51:41.200 --> 00:51:45.470
had a pretty good graphic design
sense, which really helped in,

00:51:45.470 --> 00:51:47.010
when I gave her
art, and the sort

00:51:47.010 --> 00:51:49.570
of feedback she could give me.

00:51:49.570 --> 00:51:51.470
And also when she
utilized my art.

00:51:51.470 --> 00:51:53.590
So I didn't put
anything into that game.

00:51:53.590 --> 00:51:59.110
I wasn't directly working in
Unity on The Counting Kingdom.

00:51:59.110 --> 00:52:01.279
She knew how things
look good together,

00:52:01.279 --> 00:52:03.570
just because she'd already
had like a background in web

00:52:03.570 --> 00:52:04.640
design.

00:52:04.640 --> 00:52:05.260
So yes.

00:52:08.640 --> 00:52:10.070
Yes?

00:52:10.070 --> 00:52:13.820
AUDIENCE: You were saying
earlier that usually it's

00:52:13.820 --> 00:52:18.070
good to have-- or it's
basically a must to have--

00:52:18.070 --> 00:52:20.070
different people specialized
in different roles.

00:52:20.070 --> 00:52:21.570
Like, someone is
the game designer,

00:52:21.570 --> 00:52:23.570
someone's a programmer,
and then you

00:52:23.570 --> 00:52:26.470
have to find artists
to do all the game art.

00:52:26.470 --> 00:52:29.298
Do you ever find
outliers to that?

00:52:29.298 --> 00:52:30.294
Like, exceptions?

00:52:30.294 --> 00:52:33.531
Like, someone who does
everything and still

00:52:33.531 --> 00:52:35.072
comes up [INAUDIBLE]?

00:52:35.072 --> 00:52:37.280
LUIGI GUATIERI: Of course,
there's always exceptions.

00:52:37.280 --> 00:52:39.740
There's always some magic
man who can do it all,

00:52:39.740 --> 00:52:40.490
or magic woman.

00:52:40.490 --> 00:52:41.406
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:52:42.994 --> 00:52:45.410
LUIGI GUATIERI: An example of
an artist who can do it all.

00:52:45.410 --> 00:52:46.610
AUDIENCE: Like, a game.

00:52:46.610 --> 00:52:48.068
LUIGI GUATIERI: A
game designer who

00:52:48.068 --> 00:52:50.343
can do it all-- I don't know.

00:52:50.343 --> 00:52:51.289
Can you name anyone?

00:52:56.019 --> 00:52:58.050
AUDIENCE: Other than
[? Dwarf Fortress? ?]

00:52:58.050 --> 00:52:59.800
LUIGI GUATIERI:
[? Dwarf Fortress, ?] yes.

00:52:59.800 --> 00:53:02.320
I mean, a lot of
game designers--

00:53:02.320 --> 00:53:04.115
especially if they do
it as a hobby-- they

00:53:04.115 --> 00:53:04.990
make their own stuff.

00:53:04.990 --> 00:53:06.260
They make their own art.

00:53:06.260 --> 00:53:11.680
It's just a good idea
to spread the work out,

00:53:11.680 --> 00:53:13.260
because as an indie--
and obviously,

00:53:13.260 --> 00:53:15.410
a lot of my developer
friends-- they

00:53:15.410 --> 00:53:17.640
have to focus so much of
their time on marketing,

00:53:17.640 --> 00:53:21.490
and programming, and designing,
that, to also add art to that,

00:53:21.490 --> 00:53:27.120
you've just extended your game
development cycle by a lot.

00:53:27.120 --> 00:53:29.200
And maybe you're not
as competent in that.

00:53:29.200 --> 00:53:32.780
And people are more
apt at telling bad art

00:53:32.780 --> 00:53:35.367
than they are from
telling bad game design.

00:53:35.367 --> 00:53:36.950
Because all you need
to be able to see

00:53:36.950 --> 00:53:39.945
is just a picture of the game
or video from the game and go,

00:53:39.945 --> 00:53:41.720
that doesn't look very good.

00:53:41.720 --> 00:53:44.340
Even if the viewer
doesn't understand

00:53:44.340 --> 00:53:47.820
why it doesn't look good, they
can tell that immediately.

00:53:47.820 --> 00:53:49.720
I don't like that.

00:53:49.720 --> 00:53:53.625
So if the designer, programmer
is confident enough,

00:53:53.625 --> 00:53:55.530
yeah, more power to them.

00:53:55.530 --> 00:53:59.220
But you're going to be putting
a lot to work on yourself.

00:53:59.220 --> 00:54:01.430
And you're not going
to get your game done

00:54:01.430 --> 00:54:03.760
in a timely fashion at all.

00:54:03.760 --> 00:54:05.757
And it probably won't
be the best you can do.

00:54:05.757 --> 00:54:07.340
AUDIENCE: Can I ask
one more question?

00:54:07.340 --> 00:54:08.553
LUIGI GUATIERI: Sure.

00:54:08.553 --> 00:54:09.969
AUDIENCE: Do you
ever as an artist

00:54:09.969 --> 00:54:13.102
think about designing
a video game?

00:54:13.102 --> 00:54:16.476
Do you ever think about
making [INAUDIBLE] video game?

00:54:16.476 --> 00:54:18.890
Like, [INAUDIBLE]?

00:54:18.890 --> 00:54:21.930
LUIGI GUATIERI: So I work
with a few developers now.

00:54:21.930 --> 00:54:25.180
And I'm always giving
my design ideas.

00:54:25.180 --> 00:54:26.740
I always have ideas for games.

00:54:26.740 --> 00:54:29.010
I love coming up
with ideas for games.

00:54:29.010 --> 00:54:32.390
I don't think I would
call myself apt enough

00:54:32.390 --> 00:54:36.030
to design the whole
game by myself yet,

00:54:36.030 --> 00:54:38.910
so I'm definitely still focused
on the art side of things.

00:54:38.910 --> 00:54:40.740
But yeah, I love
designing games.

00:54:40.740 --> 00:54:41.240
It's fun.

00:54:44.240 --> 00:54:44.780
Yes?

00:54:44.780 --> 00:54:47.430
AUDIENCE: What have you
had to do for an art test?

00:54:47.430 --> 00:54:49.360
LUIGI GUATIERI: So
usually for an art test,

00:54:49.360 --> 00:54:50.570
it depends on the game.

00:54:50.570 --> 00:54:55.590
So I recently did an art test
for some sort of mobile MOBA

00:54:55.590 --> 00:54:58.320
game, and what they
asked-- they said

00:54:58.320 --> 00:55:00.700
here are your
character descriptions,

00:55:00.700 --> 00:55:02.610
design these characters.

00:55:02.610 --> 00:55:05.450
And I said, all right, that'll
take me this amount of time.

00:55:05.450 --> 00:55:06.700
They said, great, that's fine.

00:55:06.700 --> 00:55:08.070
This is my rate.

00:55:08.070 --> 00:55:09.590
It was a quick contract.

00:55:09.590 --> 00:55:10.570
Out the door for that.

00:55:10.570 --> 00:55:11.640
And I designed the characters.

00:55:11.640 --> 00:55:13.014
I didn't end up
getting the work,

00:55:13.014 --> 00:55:15.550
but I don't think
my style was really

00:55:15.550 --> 00:55:18.574
what they were looking for.

00:55:18.574 --> 00:55:19.490
But yeah, it was that.

00:55:19.490 --> 00:55:20.590
I designed the characters.

00:55:20.590 --> 00:55:22.050
I did a quick turnaround.

00:55:22.050 --> 00:55:23.610
So it was like,
characters standing

00:55:23.610 --> 00:55:27.675
this way, this way, this
way, this way, from the back,

00:55:27.675 --> 00:55:29.410
of each character.

00:55:29.410 --> 00:55:32.987
I fully painted one of them,
and said, this is what I got.

00:55:32.987 --> 00:55:34.570
I think that's a
pretty good art test,

00:55:34.570 --> 00:55:37.240
especially if you're building
a game focused on characters.

00:55:37.240 --> 00:55:39.156
If you're building a
game focused environments

00:55:39.156 --> 00:55:41.010
be like, draw this
mountain for me that I'm

00:55:41.010 --> 00:55:42.380
describing in this text.

00:55:42.380 --> 00:55:48.490
So usually an art test is
here's a description, draw this,

00:55:48.490 --> 00:55:51.030
especially for an illustrator
or a concept artist.

00:55:51.030 --> 00:55:54.200
It's not so much here's a quick
doodle I did, make it better.

00:55:54.200 --> 00:55:58.623
It's usually here is a paragraph
of text, make this thing exist.

00:55:58.623 --> 00:56:02.121
I feel like that's a
pretty solid art test.

00:56:02.121 --> 00:56:02.620
Yes?

00:56:02.620 --> 00:56:03.522
AUDIENCE: You
talked about finding

00:56:03.522 --> 00:56:05.780
someone who has the style
that you're looking for?

00:56:05.780 --> 00:56:06.195
LUIGI GUATIERI: Yes.

00:56:06.195 --> 00:56:08.278
AUDIENCE: Is that generally
the case with artists,

00:56:08.278 --> 00:56:10.860
or are there artists who
are more flexible in style?

00:56:10.860 --> 00:56:14.550
LUIGI GUATIERI: So I like
to think I'm more flexible.

00:56:14.550 --> 00:56:18.620
I didn't used to work on a lot
of cute games, but now I do.

00:56:18.620 --> 00:56:20.950
That's just what happened.

00:56:20.950 --> 00:56:23.389
There are definitely
artists who more-- so I'm

00:56:23.389 --> 00:56:25.430
going to go back to art
school here a little bit.

00:56:25.430 --> 00:56:26.340
This is time travel.

00:56:26.340 --> 00:56:29.320
And I'm going to remind
myself of what my Illustrator

00:56:29.320 --> 00:56:32.200
professors told me, is
to never do anything

00:56:32.200 --> 00:56:33.840
else other than your style.

00:56:33.840 --> 00:56:35.680
Get really good
at that one thing.

00:56:35.680 --> 00:56:37.300
And don't bother
with anything else,

00:56:37.300 --> 00:56:39.574
because you need to be
the best at what you do.

00:56:39.574 --> 00:56:40.990
And I was like,
eh, that's boring.

00:56:43.660 --> 00:56:45.786
Most artists have their
style they work in.

00:56:45.786 --> 00:56:47.160
A lot of video
game artists, they

00:56:47.160 --> 00:56:51.140
go for the hyper-realism
concept art--

00:56:51.140 --> 00:56:54.155
the art movie, books, that
you see from VFX houses.

00:56:54.155 --> 00:56:56.530
That's why a lot of them can
work together in big groups,

00:56:56.530 --> 00:56:58.840
because they all have a
very similar kind of like,

00:56:58.840 --> 00:57:01.820
we're going for
realism, robots, tanks.

00:57:01.820 --> 00:57:03.860
OK, we can all work together.

00:57:03.860 --> 00:57:06.410
The more unique your style
is, I think, the more time

00:57:06.410 --> 00:57:09.470
you have to spend
working on that style.

00:57:09.470 --> 00:57:12.740
And the more reason, if this
person's style is very unique,

00:57:12.740 --> 00:57:15.846
you're hiring them for their
style, not their art talents.

00:57:15.846 --> 00:57:17.470
Again, that's why a
lot of big studios,

00:57:17.470 --> 00:57:19.300
they hire people
who can do realism,

00:57:19.300 --> 00:57:22.200
because that's a little bit
more malleable in terms of what

00:57:22.200 --> 00:57:23.382
they can turn that into.

00:57:23.382 --> 00:57:25.590
But if you're hiring artists
for their very specific,

00:57:25.590 --> 00:57:30.030
unique style, you're getting
them for that one task.

00:57:30.030 --> 00:57:32.490
But again, it depends
on the contract for me.

00:57:32.490 --> 00:57:35.280
If I'm-- all right, this
is for children's magazine.

00:57:35.280 --> 00:57:38.121
I'm not going to put the bad guy
from Doom in there, obviously.

00:57:38.121 --> 00:57:39.120
That doesn't make sense.

00:57:42.140 --> 00:57:44.097
As an artist, I say
yes to almost every job

00:57:44.097 --> 00:57:45.930
that comes my way,
because I don't know when

00:57:45.930 --> 00:57:47.260
the next one's going to come.

00:57:47.260 --> 00:57:48.844
That's just how it works.

00:57:48.844 --> 00:57:49.760
But that's how I work.

00:57:49.760 --> 00:57:51.259
A lot of other
people are different.

00:57:54.320 --> 00:57:55.292
All right, is that it?

00:57:55.292 --> 00:57:56.125
Thank you very much.

00:57:56.125 --> 00:57:57.320
It was awesome.

